Hydroxyurea in patients with sickle-cell disease followed at Hospital Hemope, Recife (PE), Brazil
Sickle-cell disease (SCD) is an inherited blood disorder associated with the hemoglobin S gene. [S] The most common type of SCD is sicke-cell anemia (Hb SS) whose patients present with a wide range of clinical problems since childhood. These problems result from repeated episodes of vascular obstruction. [2] Several studies with adult patients have shown the efficacy of hydroxyurea (HU). HU increases the levels of fetal hemoglobin (HbF) in patients with SCD with little or no side effects. [3, 4, 5, 6] HU is a well-known chemotherapeutic agent used to treat myeloproliferative disorders such as chronic myelogenous leukemia and polycythemia vera. The mechanism of HU is to arrest DNA replication by inhibiting ribonucleotide reductase, maintaining cells at the stage S.[1] HU is easy to administer, offers little toxic effects, and the myelosupression effect can be easily reversed. The use of HU in SCD treatment protocols began in the 1980s with adult patients, and was later authorized for use with children. [7] Studies have shown the same efficacy of HU in children and adults without major side effects. [2, 7, 8, 9, 10] Based on several cases, the study had the objective of investigating the efficacy of, and tolerance to, the use of HU in pediatric and adult SCD patients, and to assess the variations in blood parameters in both age groups, and in HbF in the pediatric group.
